05341nam a22007815i 9780812298383DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780812298383  a(DE-B1597)590443  a(OCoLC)1296425130  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBM585.2 7aHIS0220002bisacsh04a305.800942231 aKieval, Hillel J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlood Inscriptions :bScience, Modernity, and Ritual Murder at Europe's Fin de Siècle /cHillel J. Kieval. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b13 images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aJewish Culture and Contexts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tA Note on Translation, Transliteration, and Orthography -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. History and Place -- tChapter 2. Hungarian Beginnings -- tChapter 3. Roads to Prussia -- tChapter 4. The Hilsner Affair -- tChapter 5. The Many Trials of Konitz -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAlthough the Enlightenment had seemed to bring an end to the widely held belief that Jews murdered Christian children for ritual purposes, charges of the so-called blood libel were surprisingly widespread in central and eastern Europe on either side of the turn to the twentieth century. Well over one hundred accusations were made against Jews in this period, and prosecutors and government officials in Germany, Austria-Hungary, and Russia broke with long established precedent to bring six of these cases forward in sensational public trials. In Blood Inscriptions Hillel J. Kieval examines four cases—the prosecutions that took place at Tiszaeszlár in Hungary (1882-83), Xanten in Germany (1891-92), Polná in Austrian Bohemia (1899-1900), and Konitz, then Germany, now in Poland (1900-1902)—to consider the means by which discredited beliefs came to seem once again plausible.Kieval explores how educated elites took up the accusations of Jewish ritual murder and considers the roles played by government bureaucracies, the journalistic establishment, forensic medicine, and advanced legal practices in structuring the investigations and trials. The prosecutors, judges, forensic scientists, criminologists, and academic scholars of Judaism and other expert witnesses all worked hard to establish their epistemological authority as rationalists, Kieval contends. Far from being a throwback to the Middle Ages, these ritual murder trials were in all respects a product of post-Enlightenment politics and culture. Harnessed to and disciplined by the rhetoric of modernity, they were able to proceed precisely because they were framed by the idioms of scientific discourse and rationality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aBlood accusationzEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszEuropexSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aScience and lawzEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aTrials (Murder)zEuropexHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aHistory.  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022 Englishz978311099454408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2022z9783110994537oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn